title: For Sale:  Matching pair of Colt Woodsman .22LR pistols
postcontent:
SPF

A curious tale of two young men and their purchases of Colt Woodsman pistols. In 1939 a young fellow in Northern California purchased a new 6+ inch Colt Woodsman and a year later, in 1940, another young fellow in Southern California purchased a new 4+ inch Colt Woodsman.

They both kept them until, late in life, they passed them on to family members to keep. Those families both moved to Myrtle Creek, Oregon, and purchased houses next door to each other. It was not until years later that they both realized the fate of those two pistols. They originally had been separated by 100s of miles and a year of birth, and now they are only 100 feet apart after all the intervening years.

Both of these Colts pistols are in .22LR, the shorter one having been shot and carried more than the longer barreled one. Both are in very nice condition, shoot great, and would make a great addition to any collection. Grips and magazines are the same for both pistols.

The larger one, from 1939, has a barrel length of 6 and 5/8 inches, the smaller one, from 1940, has a barrel length of 4 and ½ inches. The smaller one also has a removable trigger shoe installed. Both pistols come with a factory 10 round magazine, and there is an extra non-factory magazine. Both pistols come with their original grips and there are two additional plastic aftermarket grips. Both pistols also come with leather holsters – the larger holster is in very nice condition and dates from the same era. The smaller holster is in poor shape, good for a pattern or can be used in a display.

The pistols are being sold as a set, along with the extras as a part of the set. I can not separate the pistols or the extras – it is a purchase all or nothing sale. Asking price is a reasonable $1,300.

These are for sale only, not for trade. If you are interested and need more information or more pictures, please call Ken at REDACTED. If you wish to purchase, I am located in Myrtle Creek, just south of Roseburg a few miles, and just off of I-5 at milepost 108.
